Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<T>`** — it hosts your app in-memory and gives you an `HttpClient` you can hand to the MCP C# SDK's transport. No real port is opened.

### Setup

```bash
dotnet add package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
dotnet add package ModelContextProtocol  # MCP C# SDK
```

### Example test

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing;
using ModelContextProtocol.Client;
using ModelContextProtocol.Protocol.Transport;

public class McpIntegrationTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly WebApplicationFactory<Program> _factory;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
        => _factory = factory;

    [Fact]
    public async Task ListTools_ReturnsExpectedTools()
    {
        // WebApplicationFactory gives you an HttpClient backed
        // by an in-memory test server — no real port needed.
        var httpClient = _factory.CreateClient();

        // Use the SDK's Streamable HTTP transport, injecting
        // the test HttpClient so traffic stays in-process.
        var transport = new SseClientTransport(
            new SseClientTransportOptions
            {
                Endpoint = new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/mcp"),
                Name = "test-client"
            },
            httpClient          // ← key: pass the factory's client
        );

        await using var mcpClient = await McpClientFactory.CreateAsync(
            transport,
            cancellationToken: CancellationToken.None
        );

        var tools = await mcpClient.ListToolsAsync();

        Assert.NotEmpty(tools);
        Assert.Contains(tools, t => t.Name == "my-tool");
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task CallTool_ReturnsCorrectResult()
    {
        var httpClient = _factory.CreateClient();
        var transport = new SseClientTransport(
            new SseClientTransportOptions
            {
                Endpoint = new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/mcp"),
                Name = "test-client"
            },
            httpClient
        );

        await using var mcpClient = await McpClientFactory.CreateAsync(transport);

        var result = await mcpClient.CallToolAsync(
            "my-tool",
            new Dictionary<string, object?> { ["input"] = "hello" }
        );

        Assert.False(result.IsError);
        Assert.Contains("expected-output", result.Content[0].Text);
    }
}
```

### Key points

| Concern | Approach |
|---|---|
| **No real server** | `WebApplicationFactory` hosts in-process; `CreateClient()` returns an `HttpClient` that talks over an in-memory channel |
| **Full protocol fidelity** | The MCP SDK transport sends real SSE/HTTP requests — you're testing serialization, routing, and handlers end-to-end |
| **Config overrides** | Override `ConfigureWebHost` on the factory to swap services (e.g., mock databases) |
| **`Program` visibility** | Add `<InternalsVisibleTo Include="YourTestProject" />` or a partial class `public partial class Program { }` in your server project |

> **Tip:** If your server uses the newer *Streamable HTTP* transport instead of SSE, swap `SseClientTransport` / `SseClientTransportOptions` for `StreamableHttpClientTransport` / `StreamableHttpClientTransportOptions` — the same `HttpClient` injection pattern works.
